<TITLE> Cabinet alters Supreme Judicial Commission Ordinance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 1 (bdnews24.com)The cabinet Sunday approved amendments to the Supreme Judicial Commission Ordinance 2008, bringing changes to the structure of the commission. The approval was given at a cabinet meeting held at the Chief Adviser's Office, the CA's press secretary Syed Fahim Munaim told reporters. According to the amended ordinance, the Supreme Judicial Commissionformed to select judges for the president to appoint them to the Supreme Courtwill no longer include any member of ruling and opposition parties or any secretary to the government. The number of commission members will remain the same as before: nine. The commission led by the chief justice will include the law, justice and parliamentary affairs minister or adviser, three senior judges of the Appellate Division, two senior judges of the High Court Division, attorney general and Supreme Court Bar Association chief. The president approved the ordinance on March 16, but it ran into a legal battle in the Supreme Court. SC lawyer Idrisur Rahman filed a writ petition with the HC against the ordinance and the court on April 28 slapped a three-month stay order on the legislation. On the other hand, the Appellate Division put freezes on the HC stay order on May 20 after the government filed a counter-petition. bdnews
